Each additional unit of variable attitude is associated with about 3.4 unit increase in points.
Each additional unit of variable stra is associated with about 0.85 unit increase in points.
Each additional unit of variable surf is associated with about 0.59 unit decrease in points.

The null hypothesis for each variable is that the variable has no effect on target variable (points). Pr(>|t|) in the summary is the p-value associated with this test.

Variables stra and surf do not have a statistically significant relationship with the points, so let’s fit a new model without them:

model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)

## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

Now each additional unit of variable attitude is associated with about 3.53 unit increase in points.

R2 is the proportion of the variation in the target variable that is explained by the model. Here it is 0.1906, so this model explains about 19% of the variation in points.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model2, which=c(1,2,5))

In addition to the linearity assumption the model assumes that the errors are not correlated and that their size is not dependent on the explanatory variables. The model also assumes:

-Constant variance of errors. The residuals vs fitted plot seems passable. The points are rather concentrated in the middle in the higher end of the fitted values, but then again the number of those points is small, which might be the reason for smaller observed variance.

-Normality of the errors. The qq-plot is passable but is a bit weird at the ends.

The residuals vs leverage plot seems fine. No single data point particularly stands out.

The data has 51 variables and 370 rows, and is about Portugese students.

4 chosen variables of interest:
age - student’s age (hypothesis: high consumption could be associated with higher age)
goout - going out with friends (hypothesis: high consumption could be associated with higher goout)
failures - number of past class failures (hypothesis: high consumption could be associated with higher amount of failures)
absences - number of school absences (hypothesis: high consumption could be associated with higher amount of absences)

All of the above hypotheses seem reasonably possible based on this data. With all of the variables, the higher variable values were expected to be associated with high_use=True. The data supports these relationships at least to some extent, even though it is a bit hard to read the tables because of the class imbalance between True/False labels in high_use.

library(tidyr)

Variable age is not statistically significant in this model. Age’s confidence interval for odds ratio includes 1 which foreshadows this result.

The other variables are significant in this model, variable failures with significance treshold 0.05 and goout and absences with significance treshold 0.001. The absolute effect of absences is smaller than the other significant variables.

The odds ratios can be interpreted as ratios between unit change / no unit change in the explanatory variable. Variable goout has an odds ratio of over 2, so the unit change in high_use is twice as likely as no unit change.

Comparing the results with the previous hypotheses, the hypothesis about age is not supported by the evidence.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ goout + failures + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")

probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

t = table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
err_training = (t[1,2]+t[2,1])/sum(t)

print(paste('Training error: ', round(err_training,4)))
## [1] "Training error:  0.2378"
t
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   237   22
##    TRUE     66   45

The model performance as a whole is fairly satisfactory, but many of the instances of high_use=True are still left unidentified (66/(66+45)). In other words, the model has a rather low recall.

Comparing the model to a simple guessing strategy, if half of the time the guess about the binary output would be correct, the model is much better, because it gives the wrong answer only about 24% of the time.

Variables rad (index of accessibility to radial highways) and tax (full-value property-tax rate per $10,000) seem to be highly correlated. Other moderately strong positive correlations can be found between indus (proportion of non-retail business acres per town) and nox (nitrogen oxides concentration), nox and age (proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940), indus and tax, rm (average number of rooms per dwelling) and medv (median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s). Variables lstat (lower status of the population (percent)) and medv are negatively correlated. dis (weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres) is negatively correlated with indus, nox and age.

# Categorial variable
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label=c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)
# Dividing into training and test datasets
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Linear discriminant analysis:

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       13      13        0    0
##   med_low    4      20        1    0
##   med_high   1       8       16    2
##   high       0       0        1   23

The predictions are otherwise fairly accurate, but for class ‘low’ there are a lot of wrong predictions under the predicted label ‘med_low’. Half of the data points under the class label ‘low’ to be exact.

# PCA on standardized data
human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human <- prcomp(human_std)
biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2, cex=c(0.8, 1))

The non standardized data gives results that are hard to interpret because the scale of the variables is so different. The variable GNI, that is Gross National Income per capita, has the largest scale of values. In the upper plot GNI is the only variable that can be clearly identified to have a particularly large variance and high correlation with PC1.

The bottom plot is easier to interpret. Expected years of schooling (Edu.Exp), Gross National Income per capita (GNI), the ratio of Proportion of females with at least secondary education / Proportion of males with at least secondary education (Edu2.FM) and Life expectancy at birth (Life.Exp) are highly correlated with each other and with PC1. Maternal mortality ratio (Mat.Mor) and Adolescent birth rate (Ado.Birth) are also correlated with PC1 and each other. The ratio of Proportion of females in the labour force / Proportion of males in the labour force (Labo.FM) and Percetange of female representatives in parliament (Parli.F) are correlated with each other and PC2.

Seems like PC1 is related with wellbeing, mortality and birth -related variables, while PC2 is related with gender equality -related variables.
